Great questions, I didn’t answer right away because I wanted to give a proper response.

“Devs” is a big word in today’s landscape. Pretty much anyone can be a “dev” and build something cool. If you want a small Telegram bot that notifies you about the price of a subnet, or a simple Python script that does DCA, or even anything with AI, tools like ChatGPT, Gemini, and Claude are very friendly solutions.

If you want data from a blockchain, then you need a provider like FlameWire. We’re not yet ready to be a main player in the broader space, but for Bittensor we can confidently say we’re one of the best solutions when it comes to being an RPC provider.

A few other things are still in progress to set everything in place, the most important being:
A load balancer
Gateway deployment across multiple regions

The main reasons are: latency, pricing, and decentralization.

There’s a lot of capital flowing into RPC providers, for example, Helius ($21.5M) and Lava Network ($15M), which shows there’s still a lot of interest in this space.

Once we have everything in place, scaling will be very easy. Bittensor itself is a battleground with many challenges, and miners are always up for “optimizations.” I believe in the long run this gives us an edge to create the best environment possible.
Thanks for the feedback! We are all watching intently 😁

messages.content: Looking much better now! Good stuff

We’ve actually built on top of the indexer an observer service.
That means instead of just pulling events from RPC, we can now stream and decode them in real time, push them into queues/DB, and expose them as clean APIs. The observer adds checkpoints, retries, and fan-out (alerts, metrics, dashboards), which makes it way more reliable and scalable than querying raw RPC.
If you want to use it and contribute feel free to do so.
